full_text: In this demonstration, I have two requirements. The first is to ensure that an auto claim cannot be saved at the new loss level without a value entered in the fault rating field. First, I will create a new display key. The display key informs the user that fault rating must be specified.  I'll put my demo rule at the top of the list, so it will fire first. The rule will use the display key I created, so I need to import the display key module. This rule only applies to auto claims, where the fault rating is not set by the user. I will use the claim reject method, throwing an error at the new loss level. The display key I created will be displayed for the error. There is no warning level for this rule. The second requirement is that a null weather field on an auto claim should result in a warning, and should prevent the claim from being paid out. Also, in these cases, the weather field should be highlighted. I will need two display keys for this requirement. The first display key is for the warning. And the second one is for the error message. Now, I will create another claim validation rule. As before, I need access to display keys. Once again the rule applies to auto claims. But in this case, it's the weather field we're testing for now. This time I will use the reject field method, so the specific field will be highlighted as per the requirement. The error level is TC underscore payment. The error level is TC underscore payment. The error level is TC underscore new loss. Now, to test the rules, I will start the Claim Center server. Then, in Claim Center, I log in as Andy Applegate. Now, I'll create a new auto claim. I'll search for an insured party named Xu. With today is the lost date. I'll quickly enter the most basic information. Filogy of the ! And look what happens when I attempt to save the claim. I get the error for the fault rating, and the warning for the weather. Note that the weather field is highlighted in red. So I'll fix the fault rating, which is causing the error. This time, when I click finish, the claim is saved. So I will navigate to the claim. And on its status screen, I see that the claim cannot be validated past the Send to External System validation level. In the Actions menu, I validate the claim. At the ability to pay validation level, to see where the problem is, I see the error message about the weather field. When I click the error, Claim Center automatically navigates me to the Lost Details screen, where the weather field is located. I'll clear the error message. And edit the claim. So I can set the weather field. Then, when I save the claim, and return to the Status page, the claim is now at the ability to pay validation level. This concludes the Creating and Verifying Validation Rules demonstration.
